  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4424823180" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4424823180" />
    <a title="Phrodrick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67951314-phrodrick"><img alt="Phrodrick" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1545868348p2/67951314.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4424823180?book_show_action=true">Dec 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Phrodrick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Phrodrick" href="/user/show/67951314-phrodrick">Phrodrick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099529569" href="/book/show/7891025-a-country-doctor-s-notebook">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4424823180" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2046407337097257582">Like many another I came to A Country Doctor&apos;s Notebook Paperback by Mikhail Bulgakov having read his classic The Master and Margarita and having watched the first season of the Television series loosely based on Notebook. To my surprise I read a much warmer and humane near diary of the life of a doctor in a remote Russian village.<br/><br/> Given some of the reviews a few moment on the authors bio may be necessary. Summarized from Wiki: Mikhail Bulgakov was a medical doctor, a playwright and author in th</span>
  <span id="freeText2046407337097257582" style="display:none">Like many another I came to A Country Doctor's Notebook Paperback by Mikhail Bulgakov having read his classic The Master and Margarita and having watched the first season of the Television series loosely based on Notebook. To my surprise I read a much warmer and humane near diary of the life of a doctor in a remote Russian village.<br /><br /> Given some of the reviews a few moment on the authors bio may be necessary. Summarized from Wiki: Mikhail Bulgakov was a medical doctor, a playwright and author in the first half of the 20th century. It is reported that Stalin liked some of his work and personally banned much of it. By the beginning of World War I he was a Red Cross doctor and was sent to the front. There he was “badly injured at least twice “. The result of these injuries was that he self-medicated with morphine and became addicted. He was treated for this addiction twice and Wiki says he never touched it again, other sources are not as certain. Again, quoting directly:<br />In 1916, Bulgakov graduated from the Medical Department of Kyiv University and after serving as a surgeon at Chernovtsy hospital, was appointed provincial physician to Smolensk province. His life in those days is reflected in his A Country Doctor's Notebook.[15] In September 1917, Bulgakov was moved to the hospital in Vyazma, near Smolensk. In February 1918, he returned to Kyiv, Ukraine, where he opened a private practice at his home at Andreyevsky Descent, 13. Here he lived through the Civil War and witnessed ten coups. Successive governments drafted the young doctor into their service while two of his brothers were serving in the White Army against the Bolsheviks.<br />In February 1919, he was mobilized as an army physician by the Ukrainian People's Army and assigned to the Northern Caucasus. There, he became seriously ill with typhus and barely survived.[15][16] In the Caucasus, he started working as a journalist, but when he and others were invited to return as doctors by the French and German governments, Bulgakov was refused permission to leave Russia because of the typhus. That was when he last saw his family; after the Civil War and the rise of the Soviets most of his relatives emigrated to Paris.<br /><br /><br />Bottom line the Notebooks are based on his life. Further the journal of the morphia addicted doctor that is the last part of this book, is also drawn from life.<br /><br /><br />A country Doctor’s Notebook is a series of short stories built around the early experiences of a Russian doctor who, have just graduated from Medical school is assigned to a very remote hospital just outside of a small Russian village. He is the only Doctor in this otherwise well equipt facility. He has an assistant and some nurses. Each has experience and presumable some training, but the responsibilities and decisions are his. He has only the books left by his predecessor from which to seek advice. <br /><br />Given that this is Russian fiction the entire collect is 9 stories or episodes, totaling 158 pages. This is also the worst of Russian winter and physical plus psychological isolation, yet there is more humor and humanity than typical Russian Depression.<br /><br />My sense is that this is a very credible discussion of Medicine with no modern anything. The earliest kinds of anesthesia, what passed for antibiotics and the vast majority of modern medical specialties not even named, much less practiced. This last point being relatively unimportant, because the most our doctor could do is refer some cases to the next larger facility, and then only if there was a chance the patience could survive the trip. <br /><br />Our young doctor becomes particularly incensed by the villager’s inability to comprehend Syphilis. On his initiative he would subdivide his hospital to include a ward reserved for these patients; thereby giving him certainty that they would continue at least initial courses of treatment.<br /><br />Leaving the bottom line to the bottom line. Mikhail Bulgakov is an excellent writer. If you only know his fabulist Master and Margarita, A Country Doctor's Notebook will be a fine example of how he can handle reality. It is very possible to like and admire this almost over matched fictional doctor and this is a chance to appreciate how far we have all come forward in the practice of medicine.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2046407337097257582" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

